cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use PERK, please cite it using the metadata below."
title: "PERK: Personal Email Research Knowledge Graph"
abstract: >-
  Utilising personal information to assist us in our day-to-day
  proceedings has become a growing avenue for research and exploration.
  Emails provide a rich source of personal data, highlighting our daily ac-
  tivities and offering insights into our professional world, as they are one
  of the most pervasive forms of personal communication. Yet, it is one
  of the least tapped knowledge resources. In this paper, we describe a
  method for constructing a Personal Email Research Knowledge graph
  (PERK), which is a personal research knowledge graph (PRKG) derived
  from a researcher’s emails. PERK harvests informational entities, such
  as collaborators, publication details, scientific terminologies, and meet-
  ing minutes, from personal emails. We first developed PERKOnto, an
  ontology based on the professional requirements of a researcher. To in-
  stantiate the ontology and construct PERK, we created a synthetic email
  dataset, PATRA, using a large language model (LLM), thereby avoiding
  potential privacy risks associated with using personal emails to demon-
  strate such a knowledge graph. We subsequently extracted information
  in the form of entities, attributes, and relations from PATRA with the
  help of an LLM to create PERK. We also evaluated the quality of the
  synthetic corpus created and performed question-answering on PERK
  based on our proposed QA dataset called PRASHNA-PATRA to assess
  the overall construction and utility of the LLM-aided PERK. Code is released
  under MIT; the datasets under CC-BY-4.0.
